post_text: We have a great showing of community spirit going on at our office today. Folks from Kiwanis Club of Muncie are assembling boxes of books they purchased to donate to our K-4 students throughout the district. As part of their 100th anniversary, the group plans to create a Reading Oasis in each Muncie elementary school complete with bookshelves and bean bag reading chairs. CEO Lee Ann Kwiatkowski wanted to thank them personally for their work. What a tremendous project - we are very grateful!

post_text: At tonight's School Board meeting, The Community Foundation of Muncie and Delaware County President Kelly Shrock presented MCS Board President Jim Williams with the David Sursa Leadership Award. Ball State President Geoffrey Mearns and MCS CEO Lee Ann Kwiatkowski nominated Jim. The award is given annually to a nonprofit board member who displays the characteristics and commitment to community expressed by visionary leader David Sursa. This is a well-deserved honor for our tireless board leader. Congrats, Jim! We couldn't be doing what we do without you!

post_text: Need to get your child's shots up-to-date before school? Here's one way to do that. Check the events below to see if one of these is near you. School starts Aug. 11!
shared_text:
Open Door Pediatrics
July 23 at 1:29 PM ·

The Mobile Unit team will be out and about providing immunizations and physicals directly in neighborhoods prior to the start of school. Take advantage of this convenient way to stay up-to-date.

✅ As part of safety precautions, please schedule your child's visit in advance at (765) 286-7000.
✅ Services are open to any child in the community.
✅ Immunizations on the Mobile Unit are no-cost for those covered by Medicaid/HIP/Hoosier Healthwise, as well as those without insurance.

post_text: All MCS teachers are encouraged to take part....
shared_text:
Ball State University Teachers College
July 6 at 10:12 AM ·

Are you a P-12 educator looking for help figuring out how to successfully teach remotely? Ball State Teachers College is offering this FREE summer online professional learning series: Teaching Remotely: Professional Learning for P-12 Educators.

Open now, this self-paced series will allow teachers to explore curated, reliable resources, and make content that results in an extension of their classrooms for accessible teaching and learning in multiple contexts any time of the year.

Participating teachers from Muncie Community Schools, Burris Laboratory School, The Indiana Academy for Science, Mathematics, and Humanities, and schools authorized by the Ball State Office of Charter Schools will receive a stipend upon full completion of all modules.

Register at: https://remoteteaching.bsu.edu/

post_text:
Easy Way to Help From Home

In less than ten minutes, you can show your support for your loved ones, your neighbors, and those serving on the front lines of the COVID-19 pandemic by being counted in the 2020 U.S. Census. You may not realize it, but your participation in Census will impact the next ten years of federal funding for hospitals, schools, roads, public works, non-profit organizations, and other vital programs in Muncie and Delaware County.

Unfortunately, less than half of Muncie and Delaware County residents have completed the census so far. Please take a few moments today to get everyone in your household counted – including babies, children, and anyone else living with you. You can do it right from home at www.my2020census.gov or 844-330-2020. All responses are completely confidential, private, and secure. You can use the Census ID you received in the mail last month, but it Is not necessary.

Remember, ten minutes equals ten years of critical support to our community!

City of Muncie
October 30, 2019 at 10:20 AM ·

2019 HALLOWEEN TRICK OR TREATING HOURS:

Due to the weather....Trick or Treating hours will be on FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 1ST FROM 5PM TO 9PM.

Be Safe. Watch out for little goblins!! And...have fun!!

*** EDIT: For those who are upset by the change in trick or treating hours....the decision was made due to the safety of the children who will be out in the weather. They are calling for high winds, rain and possibly snow. As weather conditions forecast on Monday are not always accurate...we watched to see if anything would change. We understand that this is difficult for parents, but our priority is the safety of the children running around in wind and rain and snow who could possibly be hit by a car that cannot either see them because of the weather conditions or stop in time because of the slick conditions. We hope that you can take your kids out on Friday when the weather will be much better, but we stand by our decision to keep the event as safe as possible.

SAFETY TIP LINE (765-747-1632)

Muncie Community Schools operates a Safety Tip Line which is available to anyone who wants to report information related to school safety in a confidential manner. The number can be reached 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. Calls are anonymous and confidential. Examples of information may include bullying, drugs and/or alcohol use or presence, weapons, violence and/or threats, theft and anything else that maybe a threat to students, staff and the school.

post_text:
We are currently searching for caring and energetic substitute teachers to join Muncie Community Schools. Please go the the Muncie Community Schools website, http://www.muncie.k12.in.us/human_resources to apply.

Substitute teachers are employed on an as-needed basis whenever school is in session. Individuals must have a minimum of a high school diploma. Transcripts with the highest degree earned must be provided on application. Each applicant must be able to pass a drug screen and national criminal check.

Pay is now as follows:
HS Diploma = $70 per day
60+ credit hours =$80 per day
Bachelor's Degree = $90 per day
Master's Degree = $100 per day

Currently there will be two sessions open to the public scheduled at Muncie Public Library locations on: June 12 6-7:30 p.m. at Maring Hunt and July 29th 6:30-8 p.m. at Kennedy Library. BALLSTATEDAILYNEWS.COM
Ball State, MCS communities submit ideas for academic innovation plan

Ball State Office of Community Engagement
May 22, 2019 at 4:44 PM ·

More than 120 community members came out to "dream big" about Muncie Community Schools. While every idea may not become a reality, they all will be considered as part of the innovation planning process.

Additional community conversations, to be led by the United Way of Delaware and Henry Counties, will be available this summer. You also are encouraged to share your ideas at www.bsu.edu/mcsfeedback.

Whether or not you have children in the Muncie Community Schools, the success of our community is directly linked to the success of our public schools. Everyone is encouraged to play a part and share their ideas!

THESTARPRESS.COM
'Learning is fun in her classroom': MCS teacher wins $15,000 Ball Bros. Foundation grant
text:
THESTARPRESS.COM
'Learning is fun in her classroom': MCS teacher wins $15,000 Ball Bros. Foundation grant

shared_text:
Ball Brothers Foundation
May 8, 2019 at 4:25 PM ·

In Erica Collins’ 6th grade science classroom at Northside Middle School, students are called “scientists.” Whether they are performing experiments, “investigating” solutions to challenges, or writing papers to summarize their findings, Collins’ “scientists” are learning critical thinking, problem-solving, and collaboration skills that will prepare them for the future. “Today’s students must be motivated to learn and confident to tackle new things…my students will grow to adulthood in a different world than the one they live in now,” shared Collins’ in reflecting on her teaching philosophy. Collins—also a math and computer teacher—is the winner of our 2019 Excellence in Teaching Award. She was selected from a pool of nominees from public schools across Delaware County. Congratulations, Erica! Learn more here: https://ballfdn.org/ball-brothers-foundation-announces-2019-excellence-in-teaching-award-winner/
